    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h4>How do I know if an equipment financing company is legitimate?</h4>

    <p>Check for a registered business license with Suruhanjaya Syarikat Malaysia (SSM), verify their physical office address, and look for online reviews from other businesses. Legitimate companies are transparent about their registration and contact details.</p>

    <h4>Can I use equipment financing if I have CCRIS issues?</h4>

    <p>Yes, you can. While banks are strict about CCRIS, alternative financiers like Ing Heng Credit look at the full picture — your revenue, equipment value, and business potential. Minor CCRIS issues don't automatically disqualify you.</p>

    <h4>What's the difference between a bank and an equipment financing company?</h4>

    <p>Banks are more rigid, slower, and have stricter approval criteria. Specialized equipment financing companies are faster, more flexible, and understand industry-specific cash flow patterns. If you need speed and flexibility, a specialized financier is usually better.</p>

    <h4>How long does equipment financing approval take?</h4>

    <p>With Ing Heng Credit, most approvals happen within 24-48 hours after receiving complete documents. Banks can take 2-3 weeks or longer.</p>

    <h4>Can I finance used equipment?</h4>

    <p>Yes. We finance both new and used equipment, provided it's in good condition and has resale value. Some banks only finance new equipment — another advantage of working with specialized financiers.</p>

    <h4>What happens if my equipment breaks down?</h4>

    <p>Your obligation to continue loan payments remains regardless of equipment condition. We recommend insurance coverage for equipment, which we can help arrange. Some financiers offer payment deferral options in genuine hardship cases — ask about this upfront.</p>

    <h4>Can I pay off my equipment loan early?</h4>

    <p>Yes, we allow early repayment without penalties. In fact, many clients pay off loans faster than expected when business is good. Check with your financier — some charge early repayment fees.</p>

